---
description: Vitest testing conventions. Applies to all test and spec files.
globs: ["**/*.test.ts", "**/*.test.tsx", "**/*.spec.ts", "**/*.spec.tsx"]
alwaysApply: false
---

## Framework
- Vitest only — no Jest imports (`describe`, `it`, `expect`, `vi` from `vitest`).
- Run a single test file: `npm run test -- path/to/file.test.ts`.
- Run a single test: `npm run test -- -t "test name"`.
- Watch mode: `npm run test -- --watch`.

## File naming and location
- Unit tests: colocated with the file they test — `foo.ts` → `foo.test.ts`.
- Integration tests: `src/__tests__/integration/`.
- Test utilities and fixtures: `src/__tests__/helpers/`.
- Never name a test file `index.test.ts` — name it after what it tests.

## Structure
```typescript
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from 'vitest'

describe('ComponentOrFunction', () => {
  describe('methodOrScenario', () => {
    it('does X when Y', () => {
      // Arrange
      const input = ...

      // Act
      const result = fn(input)

      // Assert
      expect(result).toBe(expected)
    })
  })
})
```

## Naming
- Test names are full sentences: `'returns null when user is not found'`
  not `'null user'` or `'test 1'`.
- `describe` block = the thing being tested.
- Nested `describe` block = the scenario or method.
- `it` = the specific behaviour being verified.

## What to test
- Public behaviour — inputs and outputs, not internal implementation.
- Happy path: one or two tests maximum.
- Error paths: every thrown error, every rejected promise.
- Edge cases: null, undefined, empty string, empty array, zero, negative.
- Boundary conditions: off-by-one, max/min values.

## What not to test
- Private methods or internal variables.
- Third-party library behaviour — mock it, don't test it.
- Simple getters/setters with no logic.
- Implementation details that could change without behaviour changing.

## Mocking
- Use `vi.mock()` for modules, `vi.spyOn()` for methods.
- Mock at the boundary — mock HTTP clients, mock `fetch`, mock external services.
- Never mock the thing you are testing.
- Reset mocks between tests: use `beforeEach(() => { vi.clearAllMocks() })`.

## Assertions
- One logical assertion per test — multiple `expect` calls are fine if they
  describe the same outcome.
- Prefer specific matchers: `toEqual`, `toContain`, `toThrow` over `toBeTruthy`.
- For async: `await expect(promise).resolves.toBe(x)` or
  `await expect(promise).rejects.toThrow(ErrorClass)`.

## Do not
- Do not use `test.skip` without a comment explaining why and a ticket reference.
- Do not use `test.only` in committed code.
- Do not make real HTTP requests or real DB calls in unit tests.
- Do not share mutable state between tests — each test sets up its own state.
- Do not assert on implementation details like call counts unless the call
  itself is the observable behaviour being tested.
